Package ohos.ivihardware.vehiclecontrol

Class VehicleChassisManager

  • java.lang.Object
    • ohos.ivihardware.vehiclecontrol.VehicleChassisManager

  • public class VehicleChassisManager
extends java.lang.Object
    A public class that obtains vehicle signal information in the chassis.

    This class provides basic chassis signal identifiers and signal access methods. You can use the defined chassis signal identifiers to obtain specified signal values.

    The chassis provides signals for the following components: Axle, Wheel and Tire.

    Since:
    1
    SystemCapability
    SystemCapability.Ivi.VehicleControl

      • getVehicleSignal

        public static <T> T getVehicleSignal​(java.lang.Class<T> propClass,
                                     java.lang.String chassisPropertyId,
                                     int chassisZone)
                              throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException,
                                     ohos.rpc.RemoteException,
                                     java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException
        Obtains the signal value of a vehicle.

        You can obtain the signal value of only the specified signal in a vehicle zone. You must use a variable whose data type is the same as that of the specified signal to save the result.

        Sample code for obtaining the signal value of a vehicle: 

         int zone = VehicleZone.ZONE_NONE;
 short signalValue = VehicleChassisManager.getVehicleSignal(Short.class,
             VehicleChassisManager.ID_CHASSIS_AXLE_WHEELWIDTH, zone);
        Parameters:
        propClass - Indicates the data type wrapper for the specified signal, for example, Long.class.
        chassisPropertyId - Identifies a vehicle signal, which can be of the attribute, signal, or actuator type.
        chassisZone - Indicates the vehicle zone (default value: entire vehicle), which is defined in VehicleZone. All options of the chassisZone signal have been listed in the description of the chassisPropertyId for each vehicle.
        Returns:
        Returns the signal value. Returns the signal value of the boolean, byte, short, int, long, float, double, or string type.
        Throws:
        java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - Throws this exception if the signal is unavailable.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - Throws this exception if a parameter value is invalid.
        ohos.rpc.RemoteException - Throws this exception if an IPC error occurs.
        Since:
        1

      • getVehicleSignalMultiAreas

        public static <T> java.util.Map<java.lang.Integer,T> getVehicleSignalMultiAreas​(java.lang.Class<T> propClass,
                                                                                java.lang.String chassisPropertyId,
                                                                                int chassisZone)
                                                                         throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException,
                                                                                ohos.rpc.RemoteException,
                                                                                java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException
        Obtains the values of a specified signal from multiple vehicle zones.

        The data type can be boolean, byte, short, integer, long, float, double, or string. You must use a map whose value type is the same as that of the specified signal to save the result.

        Sample code for obtaining signal values from multiple vehicle zones: 

         int zone = VehicleZone.ZONE_ROW1;
 Map<Integer, Boolean> valueMap = VehicleChassisManager.getVehicleSignalMultiAreas(Boolean.class,
 VehicleChassisManager.ID_CHASSIS_AXLE_WHEEL_BRAKE_FLUIDLEVEL, zone);
        Parameters:
        propClass - Indicates the data type wrapper for the specified signal, for example, Long.class.
        chassisPropertyId - cabinPropertyId Identifies the vehicle signal, for example, ID_CHASSIS_ACCELERATOR_PEDALPOSITION. The node type can be attribute, signal, or actuator.
        chassisZone - Indicates the vehicle zone, which is defined in VehicleZone. All zone options have been listed in the description of chassisPropertyId for a vehicle signal (such as ID_CHASSIS_AXLE_WHEEL_BRAKE_BRAKESWORN). For example, the value ZONE_NONE indicates all the four vehicle zones, and the value ZONE_ROW1 indicates that the left and right areas of the first row.
        Returns:
        Returns a map of key-value pairs to store the signal values from multiple vehicle zones. In the map, keys are the vehicle zones defined in VehicleZone, and values are the signal values from the specified zones. The data type can be boolean, byte, short, integer, long, float, double, or string.
        Throws:
        java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - Throws this exception if the signal is unavailable.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - Throws this exception if a parameter value is invalid.
        ohos.rpc.RemoteException - Throws this exception if an IPC error occurs.
        Since:
        3

      • setVehicleActuator

        public static <T> void setVehicleActuator​(java.lang.String chassisProperty,
                                          int chassisZone,
                                          VehicleActuatorCallback callback,
                                          T value)
                                   throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException,
                                          ohos.rpc.RemoteException,
                                          java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException
        Sets the actuator value of a vehicle.

        The actuator can be a unique signal in the entire vehicle or a signal of the same type in a zone of the vehicle. If the setting is successful, no value is returned.

        Sample code for setting the actuator value of a vehicle: 

         String propId = VehicleChassisManager.ID_CHASSIS_PARKINGBRAKE_ISENGAGED;
 int zoneId = VehicleZone.ZONE_NONE;
 Boolean value = true;
 VehicleActuatorCallback callback = new VehicleActuatorCallback() {
     @Override
     public void onErrorActuator(String propId, int zoneId, int outResult) {
     }
 };
 VehicleChassisManager.setVehicleActuator(propId, zoneId, callback, value);
        Parameters:
        chassisProperty - Identifies a vehicle signal, which can be of the actuator type.
        chassisZone - Indicates the vehicle zone (default value: entire vehicle), which is defined in VehicleZone. All options of the chassisZone signal have been listed in the description of the chassisProperty for each vehicle. Multiple values of chassisZone can be combined, for example, you can set chassisZone to ZONE_ROW1 | ZONE_POS1 and ZONE_ROW1 | ZONE_POS2 to get their intersection ZONE_ROW1.
        callback - Indicates the setting error callback.
        value - Indicates the assigned signal value.
        Throws:
        java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - Throws this exception if the signal is unavailable.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - Throws this exception if a parameter value is invalid.
        ohos.rpc.RemoteException - Throws this exception if an IPC error occurs.
        Since:
        1

      • subscribeVehicleSignal

        public static VsSubscription subscribeVehicleSignal​(java.lang.String chassisPropertyId,
                                                    int chassisZone,
                                                    VehicleSignalCallback chassisCallback,
                                                    SubscriberFilter filters)
                                             throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException,
                                                    ohos.rpc.RemoteException,
                                                    java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException
        Subscribes to the signal value of a vehicle.

        This is an asynchronous method. The signal value must be of only the specified signal in a vehicle zone.

        Sample code for subscribing to the signal value of a vehicle: 

         private class VehicleChassisManagerTestSubCallback implements VehicleSignalCallback {
     @Override
     public void onChangeSignal(PropertyInfo propInfo) {
     // default implementation empty
     }
     @Override
     public void onErrorSignal(String propId, int zoneId, int errorCode) {
     // default implementation empty
     }
 }
 SubscriberFilter testFilter = new SubscriberFilter();
 VehicleChassisManagerTestSubCallback testCallback = new VehicleChassisManagerTestSubCallback();
 String propId = VehicleChassisManager.ID_CHASSIS_PARKINGBRAKE_ISENGAGED;
 int zoneId = VehicleZone.ZONE_NONE;
 VsSubscription result = VehicleChassisManager.subscribeVehicleSignal(propId, zoneId, testCallback, testFilter);
        Parameters:
        chassisPropertyId - Identifies a vehicle chassis signal, which can be of the actuator and sensor type.
        chassisZone - Indicates the vehicle zone (default value: entire vehicle), which is defined in VehicleZone. All options of the chassisZone signal have been listed in the description of the chassisPropertyId for each vehicle.
        chassisCallback - Indicates the callback function of the subscription.
        filters - Indicates the subscription policy (SubscriberFilter), which can be interval, range, or minchange. This parameter can be default (interval 200ms, below Long.MIN_VAL, above Long.MAX_VAL, minchange 1).
        Returns:
        Returns VsSubscription if subscription is successful.
        Throws:
        java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - Throws this exception if the signal is unavailable.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - Throws this exception if a parameter value is invalid.
        ohos.rpc.RemoteException - Throws this exception if an IPC error occurs.
        Since:
        4

      • unsubscribeVChassisSignal

        public static void unsubscribeVChassisSignal​(VsSubscription subscription)
                                      throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException,
                                             ohos.rpc.RemoteException,
                                             java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException
        Unsubscribes from the chassis signal of a vehicle with the VsSubscription handle.

        No exception is thrown if the unsubscription is successful.

        Sample code for unsubscribing to the signal signal value of a vehicle: 

         private class VehicleChassisManagerTestSubCallback implements VehicleSignalCallback {
     @Override
     public void onChangeSignal(PropertyInfo propInfo) {
     // default implementation empty
     }
     @Override
     public void onErrorSignal(String propId, int zoneId, int errorCode) {
     // default implementation empty
     }
 }
 SubscriberFilter testFilter = new SubscriberFilter();
 VehicleChassisManagerTestSubCallback testCallback = new VehicleChassisManagerTestSubCallback();
 String propId = VehicleChassisManager.ID_CHASSIS_PARKINGBRAKE_ISENGAGED;
 int zoneId = VehicleZone.ZONE_NONE;
 VsSubscription result = new VsSubscription();
 result = VehicleChassisManager.subscribeVehicleSignal(propId, zoneId, testCallback, testFilter);
 VehicleChassisManager.unsubscribeVChassisSignal(result);
        Parameters:
        subscription - Identifies a subscription.
        Throws:
        java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - Throws this exception if the signal is unavailable.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - Throws this exception if a parameter value is invalid.
        ohos.rpc.RemoteException - Throws this exception if an IPC error occurs.
        Since:
        4

        Since:
